<ns3240:section xmlns:ns3240="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.introduction.j2eeApis.jdbc">

  <ns3241:title xmlns:ns3241="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Database Connectivity (JDBC)</ns3241:title>
  <ns3242:para xmlns:ns3242="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    JDBC provides an interface to SQL data stores and in particular, relational
    databases. It supports standard SQL queries and statements including pre-compiled and
    callable and batch statements as well as connection pooling.
  </ns3242:para>
  <ns3243:para xmlns:ns3243="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Database clients using JDBC are typically distributable (i.e. no installation on the
    remote machine is required and being Java, they are platform independent).
  </ns3243:para>
  <ns3244:para xmlns:ns3244="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The elegance and simplicity provided by <ns3245:literal xmlns:ns3245="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">EJB3</ns3245:literal> and the Java Persistence API
    renders direct usage of JDBC obsolete for most purposes.
  </ns3244:para>
</ns3240:section>